<br>
Even more ridiculous, there IS NO free month trial period, you pay about 50 bucks for the game and...ONE character, thats right, you get ONE and ONLY ONE character slot. If you want more character slots, you have to pay extra (like an extra buck per character slot I think)<br>
<br>
Control scheme is hard to get used to, it was built for a PS2 controller and doesn't map very well onto a keyboard. It's not totally terrible though, just a tad, console-ish.<br>
<br>
Once you get in game though....well, it's VERY VERY pretty, hella better looking than even SWG imo. Gameplay wise though, it's nothing really special. The major differences you will notice from EQ or pretty much any other major MMO are mostly cosmetic (for example, instead of horses or drogmors, you have chocobos) but it doesn't break any new ground or anything. so as said, pretty graphics and spell FX, but thats about it - otherwise, it's EQ with just a lot of window dressing. <br>
<br>
Also, given the fact the majority of the population is non-english speaking Japanese people, it's not exactly very social for us non-Japanese speakers (who I guess would be the majority) <br>
<br>
The interesting to see though is that the biggest sell factor is the Final Fantasy name slapped onto it. Some people I know will immediatly love anything Final Fantasy. You could put Final Fantasy on just about anything and people will buy it. I am hazarding a guess that this will be the first MMO for many people just because of that, and even moreso considering that it is one of the first 'true' console MMO's. <br>
<br>
So I guess to sum up my feelings, FFXI is a -good- MMO, but thats all it is. EQ veterans will not find anything new here aside from cosmetic differences.  <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://photo11.matchnet.com/beta/2003/11/03/20/31255633.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
